Some parts of Nairobi and Western will likely record light rains. The Kenya Meteorological department has said dry conditions are expected over most parts of the country, but some regions could receive isolated light rainfall. The weatherman has also warned that a few areas in northeastern and northwestern Kenya are likely to experience strong winds, with speeds exceeding 25 knots. They include Marsabit, Mandera, Wajir, Garissa, Isiolo, Turkana, West Pokot and Samburu. “Rainfall is expected over a few areas in the Lake Victoria Basin, the highlands West of the Rift Valley, the Central and South Rift Valley, the southeastern Lowlands and the highlands East of the Rift Valley,” the five-day forecast says. Counties that are likely to receive rainfall during the five days include Siaya, Kisumu, Homa Bay, Migori, Kisii, Nyamira, Trans Nzoia, Baringo, Uasin Gishu, Elgeyo-Marakwet, Nandi, Nakuru, Narok, Kericho, Bomet, Kakamega, Vihiga, Bungoma and Busia. Besides Nairobi, others are Nyandarua, Nyeri, Kirinyaga, Laikipia, Murang'a, Kiambu, Meru, Embu and Tharaka. According to MET, some areas in Western, Nyanza and Rift Valley are likely to experience morning rains and afternoon or evening showers, with a few places having thunderstorms. In Kajiado, Kitui, Makueni, Machakos and Taita Taveta, days are likely to be sunny and nights partly cloudy, a few places having afternoon showers. Mombasa, Tana River, Kilifi, Lamu and Kwale will also have sunny days and partly cloudy nights.